  "doc_id": "59668",
  "text": "There are relatively little data in the literature to support the use of conventional fractionated radiation therapy to treat trigeminal schwannomas. In a small series from the University of California at San Francisco, [CITATION_1] patients received adjuvant radiation therapy after undergoing incomplete resection. Unfortunately, this approach failed to prevent local recurrence in nearly 50% of patients. Zabel et al. [CITATION_2] used fractionated radiation therapy in a series of 13 patients with nonvestibular schwannomas. Using a median dose of 57.6 Gy with a 1.8-Gy fraction dose, tumor shrinkage or no new growth was seen in all 13 patients at a median follow up of 33 months. Such a series, albeit small and with short follow-up periods, demonstrates that radiation therapy may be effective for halting the growth of trigeminal schwannomas.",
